Clinical variable distributions


The distribution of numeric (continuous) variables was determined first. Start with M_age. Check if normally distributed. If the Shapiro-Wilk test p>0.05, then normality can be assumed.

shapiro.test(part1$M_age) # w=0.96, p=1.1e-14
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  part1$M_age
## W = 0.96079, p-value = 1.118e-14

Also check with a histogram:

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
hist(part1$M_age,probability = T, main = "Distribution of M_age" )

And a QQplot:

qqnorm(part1$M_age, main = "QQ plot for M_age in part 1", pch=19)
qqline(part1$M_age)

Shapiro-Wilk indicates no normality in the data. The data in the histogram seems to be a little skewed to the right. Additionally, the two tails of the QQ plot deviate from the middle line to the same side, this also indicates non-normality in the data. Due to this, I calculated a median with interquartile range (IQR) for distribution of this variable.

library(plyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'plyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:Hmisc':
## 
##     is.discrete, summarize
median <- median(part1$M_age, na.rm = TRUE)
iqr <- IQR(part1$M_age, na.rm = TRUE)
iqr_low <- quantile(part1$M_age, na.rm = TRUE)[2]
iqr_high <- quantile(part1$M_age, na.rm = TRUE)[4]
print(median)
## [1] 71
print(iqr_low)
## 25% 
##  60
print(iqr_high)
## 75% 
##  80
